  <h2>Why Enterprise AI Fails (and What to Do About It)</h2>
  <p>The biggest threat to your AI rollout isn’t the tech.</p>
  <p>It’s the gap between vision and execution.</p>
  <p>Here’s how it usually plays out:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>AI models with nowhere secure to live</li>
    <li>Compliance hurdles nobody scoped</li>
    <li>Security questions no one can answer</li>
    <li>A shiny demo without substance or practical solutions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>That’s not a leadership failure.</p>
  <p>It’s a structural one.</p>
  <p>And that’s what Quansight and OpenTeams were brought in to fix.</p>

  <h2>Why AI Wasn't Working in High Complaince Environments</h2>

  <h3>What They Needed</h3>
  <p>This investment firm needed:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>An AI-powered way to search their 150,000+ internal documents</li>
    <li>Security strong enough for SEC-grade scrutiny</li>
    <li>A rollout simple enough to use—without retraining a floor of analysts</li>
  </ul>
  <p>They didn’t want an empty pitch.</p>
  <p>They wanted something that worked.</p>

  <h3>How We Made It Work</h3>
  <p>We started with the questions most teams skip:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Where will the model actually live?</li>
    <li>Who gets access—and who shouldn’t?</li>
    <li>What happens when this scales?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>From there, we built what their system actually needed: a secure, modular system with analyst-friendly interfaces and audit-ready compliance logs.</p>

